## Handling User Interaction

To make a `View` interactive, you obtain its `Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait`. This trait allows you to connect to signals for various input events like clicks, presses, and long presses.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui/dali-ui.h>
#include <dali-toolkit/dali-toolkit.h> // For InputEvent

class MyInteractiveView : public Dali::ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  MyInteractiveView()
  {
    mView = Dali::Ui::View::New();
    mView.SetBackgroundColor(Dali::Color::YELLOW);
    mView.SetRequestedWidth(150.0f);
    mView.SetRequestedHeight(50.0f);

    // Get the InteractiveTrait from the View
    Dali::Ui::InteractiveTrait interactiveTrait = mView.AsInteractive();

    // Connect to the ClickedSignal
    interactiveTrait.ConnectClickedSignal(this, &MyInteractiveView::OnViewClicked);

    // Enable clickability
    interactiveTrait.SetClickable(true);
  }

  Dali::Ui::View GetView() { return mView; }

private:
  bool OnViewClicked(Dali::Ui::View view, const Dali::InputEvent& event)
  {
    // Handle the click event
    // For example, change the background color
    view.SetBackgroundColor(Dali::Color::GREEN);
    return true; // Indicate that the event was consumed
  }

  Dali::Ui::View mView;
};
```

You can also connect to `PressedChangedSignal` to detect when a view is pressed or released, and `LongPressedSignal` for long press gestures.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui/dali-ui.h>
#include <dali-toolkit/dali-toolkit.h> // For InputEvent

class MyPressableView : public Dali::ConnectionTracker
{
public:
